@3700 = ~Big ears, bigger stories. Quiet, please—he’s getting to the good part.~
@3701 = ~Shhh! If you make noise, I’ll forget where we were in the story—and where I buried my snacks.~
@3702 = ~Go away! I’ve got a warm spot, a good story, and no patience for interruptions.~
@3703 = ~Every story needs quiet to grow, like a root in the soil. You’re stomping on mine.~
@3704 = ~Please! I’m listening intently. It’s rare to find a bear with such narrative rhythm.~
@3705 = ~And that, little ones, is how the squirrel saved the oak by making the storm cough.~
@3706 = ~That was wonderful! I liked the part where the clouds cried from laughter!~
@3707 = ~You always like the funny bits. I liked when the squirrel tricked the thunder itself.~
@3708 = ~But it wasn’t fair. The beetle didn’t deserve to be squashed like that.~
@3709 = ~I still say the beetle had it coming. Stupid beetle.~
@3710 = ~It’s just a story... or is it? Maybe it really happened once.~
@3711 = ~All stories carry truth, little ones. You must listen with more than ears.~
@3712 = ~With ears like mine, I could hear even the stars whisper!~
@3713 = ~Well, mine aren’t that big, and I’m still listening! Most of the time, anyway...~
@3714 = ~Do you know another one? One with a rabbit in it?~
@3715 = ~Very well. Settle down. This is the tale of the moonlit grove and the rabbit who outran time...~
@3716 = ~Oh, not the time story again...~
@3717 = ~Shhh! I love that one.~
@3718 = ~Long ago, before even the stars had names...~
@3719 = ~Ohh!~
@3720 = ~Greetings, two-legged creatures. Listen carefully, but don't scare my little ones, will you? I'm telling stories here.~
@3721 = ~And that, little ones, is how the hedgehog tricked the sun into sleeping late, so the flowers could bloom longer.~
@3722 = ~That hedgehog was so clever! I bet he never gets sunburned.~
@3723 = ~I still think it’s rude to fool the sun. What if it gets angry?~
@3724 = ~Then we’d have night-time all the time! Imagine the nuts I could stash!~
@3725 = ~What did the sun do after? Did it chase the hedgehog?~
@3726 = ~Ah, that is another tale... for another time.~
@3727 = ~Once, the wind fell in love with a songbird, and followed her so closely it blew all her feathers the wrong way.~
@3728 = ~That's why birds look so messy after a storm! I knew it!~
@3729 = ~Is that why the wind always whistles? Because it’s lonely now?~
@3730 = ~That bird should’ve sung a lullaby. Might’ve calmed the wind down.~
@3731 = ~But what happened to her? Did she fly away?~
@3732 = ~She sang one final note so sweet, the wind carried it across the world. Some say it's still echoing, in the quiet before dawn.~
@3733 = ~And so, the tiny mouse climbed the old cloud giant’s shoulder to whisper a song into the hollow of his heart.~
@3734 = ~That’s not bravery. That’s foolishness with tiny paws.~
@3735 = ~And what good’s a song against a creature taller than ten trees?~
@3736 = ~It’s not the size of the paws—it’s the sharpness of the note.~
@3737 = ~I once gnawed through a harp string. Does that count?~
@3738 = ~If the giant had stepped on it, there’d be no tale to tell. Just pulp.~
@3739 = ~But the giant did not step. He listened. And in his stillness, the world grew a little kinder.~
@3740 = ~Welcome, traveler. Few arrive in Duskwood Dell by chance. What brings you beneath these boughs?~
@3741 = ~What is this place?~
@3742 = ~I would like to know more about the Church of Eldath here.~
@3743 = ~I'm looking for your high priest.~
@3744 = ~I'm looking for the Moist Exulted Flailweeper Alabath Bumbleditch.~
@3745 = ~I'm still looking for the Moss-Exalting Fallskipper Alatoss Boringdim.~
@3746 = ~I'm eager trying to find the Moist Exhaling Failsweeper Alatooth Brushdent.~
@3747 = ~Still no luck locating the Most Exhausted Flatkeeper Alatoast Berrydrink.~
@3748 = ~My search continues for the Most Inflated Fartsleeper Analoss Bladderbim.~
@3749 = ~I'm looking for the Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim.~
@3750 = ~I'm searching for an earthworm. Have you seen one by chance?~
@3751 = ~This is not the moment for quiet reflection.~
@3752 = ~Before you're asking: You'll find the Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim in the northeastern treehouse, near the water. Anything else?~
@3753 = ~Tell me about this place.~
@3754 = ~It’s about the Dell-Light Twins.~
@3755 = ~Greetings again. What can I do for you, seeker of peace?~
@3756 = ~May your path be soft beneath your feet, and your spirit undisturbed.~
@3757 = ~A word, <CHARNAME>. You spoke not long ago with the two little faeries who call themselves the Dell-Light Twins.~
@3758 = ~You mean those two little nuisances that keep laughing and glowing all the time?~
@3759 = ~Ah, yes — the cheerful pair who light up the Dell at night. What about them?~
@3760 = ~The Dell-Light Twins? They seemed harmless enough — a bit talkative, perhaps.~
@3761 = ~Those two faeries were delightful! Please don’t tell me something’s happened to them.~
@3762 = ~They can be a little tiresome at times, but they’ve long been part of life here in Duskwood Dell. I fear something has happened to them — they’ve vanished without a trace.~
@3763 = ~I fear they’ve come to harm... or worse — they may have been taken.~
@3764 = ~Taken?~
@3765 = ~I don’t have time for this. Ask someone else to look for them.~
@3766 = ~Taken, yes. They left the Dell at dusk, saying they wished to have an adventure. I sent an owl to keep watch — just in case.~
@3767 = ~The bird followed them along the Eshpurta Road leading toward Athkatla. It saw them speaking with a merchant, and then... they simply vanished. The merchant continued west, alone.~
@3768 = ~My owl lost sight of him, distracted by a family of mice on the roadside — she’s easily tempted. But tell me, <CHARNAME>, what kind of merchant travels that road at night, without guards? And why have the twins not returned or sent a sign since?~
@3769 = ~Perhaps they turned invisible out of fear and are hiding somewhere?~
@3770 = ~If this is another one of their pranks, I’m not falling for it.~
@3771 = ~I’ll look for them.~
@3772 = ~I don’t have time for this. Ask someone else.~
@3773 = ~I doubt it. They’ve never stayed away this long before.~
@3774 = ~I don’t have time for this.~
@3775 = ~Thank you! As I said, the merchant was headed toward Athkatla. Where he might be within that vast city, I cannot guess — but surely you know your way around better than I. Mayhap a place where merchants gather would be the best place to begin.~
@3776 = ~There’s a large marketplace there — Waukeen’s Promenade.~
@3777 = ~Do you have any description of this merchant?~
@3778 = ~He was dressed in bright red silk — quite extravagant, really. He must have been wealthy, which makes it all the stranger that he walked the Eshpurta Road alone, and at night, without any guards. He also spoke with a peculiar accent, rolling his "r"s quite distinctly. Otherwise, there was nothing unusual about him... to an owl’s eye, at least.~
@3779 = ~There’s a large marketplace in Athkatla — Waukeen’s Promenade. I’ll start my search there and look for the merchant in red silk.~
@3780 = ~Thank you for taking this upon yourself. Please, bring the twins back safely to Duskwood Dell. It would feel... emptier without their pranks and laughter.~
@3781 = ~I see. I had hoped you might lend us your aid, but I shall seek help elsewhere then.~
@3782 = ~Oh, you're looking for Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim? He can be found in one of the trees — the northeastern one, near the water. You'll most likely find him in the canopy, where he discusses difficult matters with the birds of the forest.~
@3783 = ~All right. I’ll go find him there.~
@3784 = ~Right then. Into the trees we go.~
@3785 = ~I have another question.~
@3786 = ~You must mean the Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim. Please do not mock his name—it is a sacred title. You’ll find him in the northeastern treehouse, near the water.~
@3787 = ~Strange name for a holy man, but Minsc has heard stranger! Onward to the tree with the water!~
@3788 = ~Uh, all right. I’ll go find him there.~
@3789 = ~Sorry, I'll be on my way.~
@3790 = ~Sigh. It's Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim. Please show some respect—this is a sanctuary, not a tavern full of jesters. You’ll find him in the northeastern treehouse by the water. And try to compose yourself before you speak to him.~
@3791 = ~Why are you always asking the same question, <CHARNAME>? We know the priest you’re looking for lives in the tree by the water.~
@3792 = ~Must you really mock a servant of Eldath? Their patience is not a challenge for your amusement. Show some respect.~
@3793 = ~Oh, do go on, <CHARNAME>! I so enjoy watching sanctimonious fools squirm.~
@3794 = ~Apologies. I'll head to his tree.~
@3795 = ~I’ve fought dragons with fewer names. Anyway, I'll be on my way.~
@3796 = ~Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim! Not anything else! By the still waters, how hard is that? Show some reverence or the trees themselves might sigh at your ignorance. Go on, you’ll find him by the water’s edge.~
@3797 = ~To provoke a priest of peace—what melody do you expect, my raven? A scream? A sonnet? There is no drama in still waters.~
@3798 = ~It is unwise to test the patience of one who has sworn never to lose it. There is no honor in mocking restraint.~
@3799 = ~A little blasphemy never hurt anyone—except mayhap the pride of pious weaklings.~
@3800 = ~Words sting more than blades, they say. I almost feel sorry for this moss-addled relic. Almost.~
@3801 = ~Go on then—let’s see if the priest’ll shed his peaceful skin and bare some teeth!~
@3802 = ~Forgive me, I’m just bad with so many silly—uh, I mean syllables. Bye.~
@3803 = ~It's Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim! Say it with me: Ber-en-dim! If you can’t manage that, at least keep your lips sealed while you head northeast toward his chambers.~
@3804 = ~Don’t worry, We’ll just call him Fallsy from now on.~
@3805 = ~Hah. It takes wit, not war, to make a priest of peace lose his composure. (Naturally, I excel at both.)~
@3806 = ~I meant no offense. Bye.~
@3807 = ~That’s enough. You’d do well to use the stillness of this grove to reflect on your behavior!~
@3808 = ~Do that. He’ll be glad to meet you.~
@3809 = ~Oh! Have you found them?~
@3810 = ~The merchant was a disguised Rakshasa. He had captured the twins. They’re inside this glass jar — alive and unharmed, but it won’t open.~
@3811 = ~Not yet, I’m still searching.~
@3812 = ~By the gods, what luck! Let me see that...~
@3813 = ~They look safe! Eldath be praised. Are they trapped inside that bottle?~
@3814 = ~The jar won’t open.~
@3815 = ~Try shaking it. Maybe that helps.~
@3816 = ~Shall I smash it with a hammer?~
@3817 = ~Let them stay in there. The quiet suits them.~
@3818 = ~The jar is sealed outside Duskwood Dell — but here, in this place of peace, nothing living can remain imprisoned.  Watch closely... the seal yields as easily as water parts for light.~
@3819 = ~Please, keep searching. I fear for them with every passing day.~
@3820 = ~Earthworms? You’d have to dig up the whole sacred ground to find one. No, I’m afraid I can’t help you there.~
@3821 = ~That would be all. Farewell.~
@3822 = ~You have questions? Gladly! I only hope I have answers you'll like.~
@3823 = ~I must be going.~
@3824 = ~Our church is guided by Most Exalted Fallskeeper Alatoasz Berendim, the wisest and most peace-minded of our order. All other priests you see here serve under his guidance. Unlike other faiths, we hold no rigid hierarchy — our belief in nature's harmony unites us and guides our service to the community.~
@3825 = ~Some priests are occasionally sent out to make the world a more peaceful place. We call them Freewalkers — they travel to places shown to them by our goddess, seeking to ease conflict and end strife. A dangerous path, but a worthy one.~
@3826 = ~I should be on my way.~
@3827 = ~This is Duskwood Dell — a hidden glade nurtured by the faith of Eldath, the goddess of still waters and quiet groves. It is a haven for those who seek peace and balance. Do you wish to know more?~
@3828 = ~Yes, tell me more.~
@3829 = ~No, I should be on my way.~
@3830 = ~Duskwood Dell has existed in this forest since time immemorial — when the woods were still young and untouched. The first followers of Eldath settled this glade back then. In the murmuring waters, they first heard the voice of the goddess, and built a sanctuary here in her honor.~
@3831 = ~They built no walls. The trees have embraced us ever since. We sleep in hammocks between the limbs, our breath shared with wind and leaf.~
@3832 = ~The waters around us are part of the Green Goddess Falls, sacred cascades that gather in pools at the glade before flowing on as the River Rimril, joining the Trifin Creek and eventually feeding into the Amstel River.~
@3833 = ~And what is the purpose of this place?~
@3834 = ~You've given me much to reflect on. Farewell.~
@3835 = ~The purpose of this place? What purpose does peace need? You will find no temples of carved stone here. Only open sky, and the gentle song of streams below. Peace is the will to let go of burden, blade, and bitterness, and there is no better place to let go.~
@3836 = ~Clinging to peace is cowardice dressed in silk. Helm teaches justice through righteous strength, not passive prayer.~
@3837 = ~There is beauty in stillness... but refusing to act invites ruin. Even forests must defend themselves.~
@3838 = ~No fighting? But how will evil learn its lesson? Boo and I are very good teachers!~
@3839 = ~Peace is a luxury of those not burdened with the world's reality. Nature can be as cruel as it is calm.~
@3840 = ~A stagnant concept for the meek and magicless. Power, not pacifism, shapes the Realms!~
@3841 = ~How very mortal. Come back to me when you've been torn apart and still choose kindness.~
@3842 = ~My brothers teach that peace is the goal, not the absence of conflict but the end of it. In this, I think we and the Eldathyn are not so different~
@3843 = ~The Weave isn’t peaceful. It shifts, it burns, it consumes. Can peace truly last in a world like this?~
@3844 = ~You speak of peace like it’s a place we can walk to. But I’ve never seen a road leading to this place.~
@3845 = ~Peace is for people who never had to fight for their next breath.~
@3846 = ~Maybe peace isn’t the absence of conflict... just the courage not to feed it.~
@3847 = ~Nice ideals. But I’ve found that peace only follows a blade.~
@3848 = ~Sounds great!~
@3849 = ~Thank you for your insights. I must go.~
@3850 = ~That’s enough wisdom for now. Time to move on.~
@3851 = ~Rivers do not rush to war, yet they shape the land more deeply than any army. Consider that, my <LADYLORD>. Farewell.~
@3852 = ~Look, brother! A new soul has arrived in Duskwood Dell.~
@3853 = ~Peace be upon you, dwarven seeker of stillness...~
@3854 = ~Hmph.~
@3855 = ~Tell us, brother—what is your name?~
@3856 = ~Korgan. BLOOD-Axe.~
@3857 = ~Ah. So tell us, brother—when was the last time you truly felt peace?~
@3858 = ~When I chopped off that human’s ugly head.~
@3859 = ~Uh... and when did you last hear the eternal silence?~
@3860 = ~When I cut out that halfling’s jabbering tongue.~
@3861 = ~With such an attitude you’ll have a hard time getting anyone to lend you their ears!~
@3862 = ~Never had trouble with that! Kept their ears. Made a fine necklace, that.~
@3863 = ~By Eldath, he’s beyond reach.~
@3864 = ~Aye. And proud of it!~
@3865 = ~By Eldath, you have problems with your temper!~
@3866 = ~No, you have problems with your delusions!~
@3867 = ~He’s beyond reach.~
@3868 = ~Peace is a gift easily overlooked, gnomish philosopher. Wouldn’t you rather sit quietly and listen to the forest breathe?~
@3869 = ~Ah, breathing! Folk never give it the credit it deserves. You breathe without thinkin’, and the moment you do think about it, you start worrying—Am I doing it right? Too shallow? Too deep? What if I forget? My Aunt Belka tried holding her breath to stay young once. Turned blue, she did, but she claimed it worked—looked twenty years younger when they buried her.~
@3870 = ~By the way, listening to breathing’s how I found out my cousin Jaffin wasn’t dead after all. Terrified the undertaker. Whole business went under. Literally—he dug himself in.~
@3871 = ~I see… even air is not safe from your stories.~
@3872 = ~Greetings, spellcasting elf.~
@3873 = ~*Half*-elf.~
@3874 = ~Your magic seems to flow gently, like water over stone.~
@3875 = ~Mine’s more like water over cliff. With steam. And screaming.~
@3876 = ~We... see. Perhaps Eldath tests our patience through you.~
@3877 = ~Hey, that makes two of us!~
@3878 = ~Blessed be the still waters! A drow who has turned from darkness — what a wondrous thing to behold!~
@3879 = ~I turned from one darkness only to find another, rivvil.~
@3880 = ~Still, to walk beneath the sun and live... you must feel peace at last?~
@3881 = ~Peace? The sun burns my skin, the surf grates my ears, and every fool priest wishes to wash my soul. I endure, I do not rejoice.~
@3882 = ~Mayhap in time, the surface will embrace you as surely as Eldath would.~
@3883 = ~The surface embraces nothing. It tolerates. Much like your goddess, I suspect.~
@3884 = ~I... see. Mayhap not all rivers seek the same sea.~
@3885 = ~Or perhaps some waters run black for a reason.~
@3886 = ~May Eldath’s peace find you yet, even if she must search long.~
@3887 = ~Fierce warrior, have you ever considered asking your foes to surrender *before* charging at them?~
@3888 = ~Of course I have! I always shout "Surrender!" while charging. They always refuse, as my swords reach them first.~
@3889 = ~Perhaps... you could wait for an answer next time?~
@3890 = ~But waiting gives evil time to think! Better to bonk them before they bolt!~
@3891 = ~That path of thought bears further walking.~
@3892 = ~A thoughtful point, brother.~
@3893 = ~Peaceful thoughts lead to clear insight.~
@3894 = ~A petal of truth, carried on calm wind.~
@3895 = ~It is a view worth holding to the light.~
@3896 = ~A still pond reflects more clearly than a rushing stream. Action must follow reflection.~
@3897 = ~Stillness is the essence of Eldath’s teaching. In silence, we find truth.~
@3898 = ~Silence, yes—but not passivity. Even the river flows, though it makes no noise in the deep.~
@3899 = ~And yet, a still pool reflects more clearly than rushing water. Action must come only after reflection.~
@3900 = ~Uh, excuse me—~
@3901 = ~I'll be on my way.~
@3902 = ~Reflection without movement is stagnation. Peace must walk the land, not only dream beneath it.~
@3903 = ~Then we are agreed, perhaps: peace is not the absence of motion, but its guidance.~
@3904 = ~Well said. May our steps remain light, and our purpose rooted.~
@3905 = ~Hello? Are you even listening?~
@3906 = ~Ah—by Eldath’s grace, there’s someone here! Forgive us, traveler, we're busy reflecting.~
@3907 = ~War is the great wound of the world. Wherever it passes, peace must struggle to grow again.~
@3908 = ~True—but some say without war, peace would have no meaning. What do we tell them?~
@3909 = ~That peace is not the absence of pain, but the healing that follows. War is a fire; peace is the rain.~
@3910 = ~Sorry to interrupt, but—~
@3911 = ~And yet some rains come too late. I have seen fields scorched beyond all tending.~
@3912 = ~Even the blackest earth may bloom again, if given time and care. Eldath does not give up on any soil.~
@3913 = ~I think I’ll wait until you’re done.~
@3914 = ~And in time, may flowers grow where banners once stood.~
@3915 = ~Oh! Eldath preserve us—someone was listening this whole time!~
@3916 = ~Then may <PRO_HESHE> carry peace in <PRO_HISHER> heart... and patience in <PRO_HISHER> ears.~
@3917 = ~Water is the voice of Eldath. It sings in streams and whispers in the mist.~
@3918 = ~And yet it has no shape of its own. It takes the form of all things, and resists none.~
@3919 = ~Beautiful words, but I only wanted to ask—~
@3920 = ~That is its strength. In yielding, it endures. In softness, it wears down stone.~
@3921 = ~And when troubled, it reflects nothing. It reminds us to still our thoughts.~
@3922 = ~Ah—Eldath’s blessings! We didn’t notice you there, friend. You haven’t been waiting long, I hope. Now, where were we?~
@3923 = ~The bees teach us much: they labor in silence, ask for nothing, and still leave behind sweetness and healing.~
@3924 = ~I make my honey slow and gently filtered, as Eldath would want it. No smoke, no fire—only patience and cool hands.~
@3925 = ~Honey calms the throat, seals wounds, and carries the scent of every flower it was born from. It is a quiet blessing in golden form.~
@3926 = ~Each jar I seal is a little peace preserved. When the world stings, a spoon of honey reminds us that not all things hurt.~
@3927 = ~The garden teaches us: Grow in silence, protect what is gentle, and bloom only when the time is right.~
@3928 = ~War wounds the world. Flowers help it heal. Eldath knew what she was doing when she gave us petals instead of blades.~
@3929 = ~Peace takes root slowly—like a flower in spring. You can’t force it open. You can only care for the soil and wait.~
@3930 = ~May your anger wither like frost at dawn, and may your words bloom like soft meadow flowers.~
@3931 = ~Some say flowers are fragile. I say they are brave—for they bloom even knowing how short their season may be.~
@3932 = ~I speak with the plants each morning. They never rush, never shout, and yet they grow just fine.~
@3933 = ~Violence may trample the field—but give it time, and green will return. Always.~
@3934 = ~Not all healing comes through herbs. Sometimes, a quiet place and the scent of blooming things are enough.~
@3935 = ~Have you found the plant yet?~
@3936 = ~No, not yet.~
@3937 = ~I have the plant here with me.~
@3938 = ~I'm not going to help you after all.~
@3939 = ~You’ve spoken with the High One, haven’t you? Alatoasz sent you after the Talona priest... and the flower. The Groveglove. Everyone whispers of it. A poison so pure even the gentle hands of Eldath cannot undo it.~
@3940 = ~We haven't met yet. My name is Mannatarv. I am old and sick, very sick. All I want is to die. But the Eldathyns won't let me.~
@3941 = ~We've met before. My name is Mannatarv. You know I am old and sick, very sick. All I want is to die. But they won't let me.~
@3942 = ~The priests heal me every day. They pour their light into me, knit my wounds, call me back when I slip away. But I am tired. My bones rot, my breath burns. Each day they gift me is another day of pain. I want no more gifts.~
@3943 = ~I beg you: Bring me a fragment of that flower before they make an antidote. Just a single leaf. Let me ingest its venom and be done. Let me leave this world in silence, not in their endless chants.~
@3944 = ~A soul begging for the kiss of death. I would grant it gladly… but not swiftly.~
@3945 = ~We must not meddle with the path of nature. Life and death are not ours to grant.~
@3946 = ~Why waste words? If he wants death, let’s grant it. No need for some poisoned flowers, though.~
@3947 = ~Some burdens may be heavier than any man can carry.~
@3948 = ~If his time has come, the river of life will claim him. We should not hasten its current, nor hold it back.~
@3949 = ~Mercy and murder walk a fine line here. I could not in good conscience aid him.~
@3950 = ~Such thoughts are blasphemy. It is not for us to grant an easy death.~
@3951 = ~Life is suffering. If he craves the end, I’ll cut it short for him gladly.~
@3952 = ~His misery is not our concern. Just keep him from delaying us.~
@3953 = ~If the old fool wants to croak, hand him the bloody weed.~
@3954 = ~You want to kill yourself with this plant?~
@3955 = ~No. I won’t be party to your death.~
@3956 = ~If this is your wish, I will bring it to you.~
@3957 = ~Perhaps there is another way.~
@3958 = ~Why wait for the plant? I can give you a quick death myself.~
@3959 = ~Huh... another visitor. Spare me your cheer, stranger. Words are heavy, and I have little strength left to carry them.~
@3960 = ~The priests fuss enough over me already. Let an old man keep to himself, for I have no life left worth speaking of. Better leave me to the scraps of existence that remain.~
@3961 = ~I meant no harm.~
@3962 = ~You sound unwell. Can I do something for you?~
@3963 = ~Hmph. No, nothing you can mend. My flesh betrays me, my bones gnaw at me, and still they will not let me go. Better to leave me be, before you waste your pity here.~
@3964 = ~As you wish. Farewell.~
@3965 = ~Enough words… each one wears me thinner. Farewell.~
@3966 = ~Still here? Hm. I've no fresh words for you... only the same old pain. Go on, stranger. Let the wind carry your steps elsewhere.~
@3967 = ~Very well. Farewell.~
@3968 = ~You're actually bringing it to me? You're a good <PRO_RACE>! Let me see...~
@3969 = ~So beautiful and yet so deadly... here, I'll just take one leaf. Everyone else should get the antidote, just not me...~
@3970 = ~Ugh, that tastes bitter! I didn't think that...~
@3971 = ~Then leave me to my torment. The priests will be pleased.~
@3972 = ~No! Not here, not in the sanctuary of Eldath. No blood must be spilled on this sacred ground. If you truly mean me mercy, let it be without violence.~
@3973 = ~If you wish to see it that way, yes. I see it as a release.~
@3974 = ~You... you would truly do this for me? I thank you already for even considering it. You may think me mad, but you have shown mercy where others offered only healing. I will wait for you by the stump in the water. Remember: you must give me a leaf of the plant before you bring it to Alatoasz! Once he crafts an antidote, I will have no hope left of passing peacefully from this world.~
@3975 = ~Good luck with your search, <PRO_RACE>. I’m counting on you and will be waiting for you.~
@3976 = ~Another way? No. I’ve tried everything. Even pleaded with the High Priest himself. Nothing helps. That's why I need your help.~
@3977 = ~Welcome, traveler. The boughs above have whispered of your coming. You’ve found your way to the Treetop Tavern—rest, if you wish, is easily given.~
@3978 = ~What exactly do you offer here?~
@3979 = ~Not today. Perhaps another time.~
@3980 = ~Show me what comforts you provide.~
@3981 = ~Then may the wind carry you gently, and peace follow your steps.~
@3982 = ~A place to rest beneath the open sky, cradled in the arms of the trees. Blankets warmed by the day’s sun, hammocks swaying between ancient limbs... and a soft hush, broken only by birdsong.~
@3983 = ~That sounds like something I could use.~
@3984 = ~I’ll pass, for now.~
@3985 = ~Then lie back, and let the leaves hold your weight. In this place, the world forgets its noise.~
@3986 = ~We offer shelter among these branches; sleeping places strung like nests between the limbs, for those who trust the trees to carry them.~
@3987 = ~We serve warm tea brewed from grove herbs and—should you wish—candles to ease the mind or soothe dreamless sleep.~
@3988 = ~Peace is our only true offering. But sometimes, that is more than enough.~
@3989 = ~I think I’ll stay. The world can wait.~
@3990 = ~Another time, perhaps.~
@3991 = ~*Cough, cough*! Pardon the haze! Too many wicks burning. Still... welcome! Want to buy something? *Cough*!~
@3992 = ~What exactly do you offer?~
@3993 = ~Let me see what you have.~
@3994 = ~Aren’t you afraid all these candles might set the whole tree ablaze?~
@3995 = ~Oh, no... *cough*! The smoke keeps the bugs away, and Eldath watches the flames. Besides... I only set one branch aflame last year, and my brothers and sisters were quick with their rain spells.~
@3996 = ~I'll take my leave.~
@3997 = ~Then walk in peace... *cough*... and may your flame never falter.~
@3998 = ~*Cough*...~
@3999 = ~I do have a few scrolls. *Cough*! Some simple, others woven with prayer.~
@4000 = ~All right, let me have a look.~
@4001 = ~Welcome, my <BROTHERSISTER>. You stand in a place of stillness, under the gentle grace of Eldath, the Quiet One. May her peace settle upon your heart.~
@4002 = ~I would like to see your services.~
@4003 = ~Could you tell me more about Eldath?~
@4004 = ~I see. I shall be going.~
@4005 = ~Of course, my <BROTHERSISTER>. Step softly, and let peace guide your path.~
@4006 = ~May the soft winds of Eldath guide you, <BROTHERSISTER>.~
@4007 = ~Eldath is the goddess of peace, still waters, and quiet groves. We offer sanctuary to those seeking harmony, far from the clamor of the world. No blade is drawn where her blessing lingers.~
@4008 = ~If I hear "peace" again, I swear I’ll start chopping trees. Then heads. In that order.~
@4009 = ~No sword? No smashing? Even not a little butt-kicking? How confusing...~
@4010 = ~A goddess of peace... How quaint. If she exists, she’ll be the first to bleed.~
@4011 = ~Many laughed at us when we planted the first saplings here. Yet now you stand in their shade.~
@4012 = ~Anything else?~
@4013 = ~Could I see your services?~
@4014 = ~Ah, that is much better. Forgive me. I sometimes take the form of a bear when the craving grows too great. Honey tastes sweeter when gathered with a muzzle and tongue, or so I tell myself.~
@4015 = ~Greetings again, lover of honey! What sweetness brings you back to me this day?~
@4016 = ~It is about the mead.~
@4017 = ~What are you doing here?~
@4018 = ~I shall not keep you from your honey. Farewell.~
@4019 = ~Oh! Do you bring good news, I hope?~
@4020 = ~I delivered the cask to the innkeeper of the Five Flagons.~
@4021 = ~No, there is nothing to report yet.~
@4022 = ~And? Did he pay you a proper price for it? A year’s labor went into that nectar.~
@4023 = ~He gave me one hundred gold pieces.~
@4024 = ~He gave me five hundred gold pieces.~
@4025 = ~He gave me seven hundred and fifty gold pieces.~
@4026 = ~He gave me a thousand gold pieces.~
@4027 = ~Only a hundred? That is… disappointing. Samuel must think Eldath’s peace worth less than a common ale. Still, what is done is done. I shall make do, though my heart is heavy.~
@4028 = ~Ahh, five hundred gold! That is fair recompense for a year’s tending. Eldath’s gardens will bloom brighter for it. Here, take a hundred coins for your trouble—peace is sweet, but labor must not go unrewarded.~
@4029 = ~Seven hundred and fifty! Ha! More than fair, more than I dared hope! Truly, Eldath smiles upon us today. Take these 250 gold for yourself, and know that your words have bought more than coin—they have bought respect. May your name be blessed as honey on the tongue.~
@4030 = ~A thousand gold? That is beyond generous—nay, it is wondrous! Samuel must have seen not only the worth of the mead, but the worth of peace itself. Take these 500 coins, and accept this gift as well—a cloak woven with Eldath’s blessing, proof against stings both great and small.~
@4031 = ~Now that I stand before you in my own skin again... what service might a humble monk of Eldath offer you?~
@4032 = ~I shall not keep you from your honey. Goodbye.~
@4033 = ~What am I doing? Why, I tend the bees, of course! Together we weave harmony into honeycomb, turning blossoms into liquid sunlight. It is not just honey that we make here, but peace itself—thick and golden, sweet upon the tongue.~
@4034 = ~Many wanderers pass by with burdens heavy on their shoulders, and I give them a spoonful. You would be surprised how many quarrels melt away when lips are sticky with honey.~
@4035 = ~Oh, now that you stand before me, I recognize you. You are the <PRO_RACE> from Athkatla, are you not? I would have a task for you, should you return to the City of Coin.~
@4036 = ~Why would a priest of Eldath concern himself with the City of Coin?~
@4037 = ~What is it you ask of me?~
@4038 = ~I am no errand runner for monks and mead. Find another to carry your casks.~
@4039 = ~In Athkatla there stands a house of laughter and song, the Five Flagons Inn. Its master, Samuel, is a man of wit and words—yet even such a stage may be gladdened by sweetness. Would you carry a cask of my honeymead to him? Negotiate a fair price in Eldath’s name, that the Quiet One’s temples and gardens may share in the coin.~
@4040 = ~Very well. I will deliver your honeymead to Samuel of the Five Flagons.~
@4041 = ~What do you mean by negotiating a fair price?~
@4042 = ~You likely know the ways of trade better than I. Ask for a sum that honors the worth of the mead, then return to me with the payment. With those coins, we shall purchase fresh candles and herbs for Eldath’s sanctuary here in the Dell, so that peace may be tended as carefully as the hive.~
@4043 = ~My thanks flow as freely as the hive’s nectar. May your words in that tavern be as smooth as honey, and may Samuel see wisdom in fair trade. Return to me with the payment, and I shall grant you a share, for even those who serve peace must taste a little sweetness for their labor.~
@4044 = ~Then let it be so. The hive teaches patience; perhaps another day another person will carry Eldath’s sweetness into the world.~
@4045 = ~Goodbye! Stay calm and honey-comb along.~
@4046 = ~Hive teaches us: Work in silence, guard the sweet, sting only when you must.~
@4047 = ~May your anger melt like wax before the flame, and may every word that leaves your lips be as gentle and sweet as the summer’s honey. Go in peace, stranger, and carry a little sweetness into the world.~
@4048 = ~It takes patience to make peace... just like good honey. You can’t rush the bees, you can’t rush the fighters.~
@4049 = ~May your anger melt like wax, and may your words be sweet as summer honey.~
@4050 = ~I have here a cask of honeymead from a monk of Eldath of Duskwood Dell.~
@4051 = ~By the gods, look at that golden glow! If the taste matches the hue, this is no mere peasant’s brew. A monk of Eldath, you say? How quaint—and how clever. Peace in a bottle, sweetness in a cask! My patrons will toast to harmony, and quarrels will dissolve before the first jug is empty.~
@4052 = ~The monk asked that you pay a fair price, that the Quiet One’s temples might share in the profit.~
@4053 = ~Such mead deserves no ordinary price. What will you offer for it, Samuel?~
@4054 = ~Ah, a reasonable request—and I am no miser when it comes to quality. How much would you ask for the mead?~
@4055 = ~I ask one hundred gold pieces.~
@4056 = ~I ask five hundred gold pieces.~
@4057 = ~I ask seven hundred and fifty gold pieces.~
@4058 = ~I ask one thousand gold pieces.~
@4059 = ~What a bargain! The priests of Eldath seem not to know the true worth of their drink. Here, take your hundred gold pieces.~
@4060 = ~Very well! Here, five hundred gold. A fair sum for a fair cask—tell your monk it shall bring peace to both tavern and temple.~
@4061 = ~Agreed! Seven hundred and fifty gold! The nectar is fine, the cause is finer still. May Eldath smile on my generosity—and on my patrons’ thirst!~
@4062 = ~A king’s ransom! Yet such sweetness cannot truly be measured in coin. Still—take a thousand gold. Let it be said that Samuel Thunderburp rewards excellence in both brew and deed!~
@4063 = ~Do give the Eldathyn my regards. I never thought they were capable of anything quite so... useful!~
@4064 = ~Greetings. I am the woodworker of Duskwood Dell—though, truth be told, I am a druid first. The grove guides my hands; I only follow its grain.~
@4065 = ~From fallen boughs I carve small beasts and cheerful trinkets, and from time to time I gather druidic wooden gear that finds its way to me. I even craft armor from Duskwood itself—light, sturdy, and touched by the forest’s calm. Would you like to see my wares?~
@4066 = ~Show me what you’ve got.~
@4067 = ~Not now.~
@4068 = ~Why do you carve wood?~
@4069 = ~Don’t you ever run out of trees here?~
@4070 = ~Do folk truly value your work?~
@4071 = ~Back again? The wood keeps me busy. Do you wish to look over my work?~
@4072 = ~Yes, let me see.~
@4073 = ~Not today.~
@4074 = ~It steadies the hands and the heart. A small carving can carry more comfort than coin.~
@4075 = ~If you like, I can show you what I’ve made.~
@4076 = ~I never cut living wood. Stormfall and time leave more than enough for willing hands.~
@4077 = ~Would you care to look?~
@4078 = ~Enough do. A smile paid in full is fair trade.~
@4079 = ~Shall I lay out my work?~
@4080 = ~What will it be?~
@4081 = ~Show me your work.~
@4082 = ~Another time.~
@4083 = ~Very well. The wood will wait.~
@4084 = ~As you wish. I’ll keep the shavings tidy.~
@4085 = ~Come back when the grain calls to you.~
@4086 = ~Another day, another carving. Safe paths.~
@4087 = ~Ah, friend! We thank you still. You saved our lives on the road.~
@4088 = ~Now our axe only split pumpkin, not heads. Better work. Better life.~
@4089 = ~Oh! Idea. Here, we give you old axe. As thanks. Don't need it anymore. We now use simpler axe, one that is only good for pumpkins.~
@4090 = ~Axe helped us find our way to Eldath. Maybe it will help you, too.~
@4091 = ~Good to see you're doing well.~
@4092 = ~I'm surprised you actually made it here.~
@4093 = ~I'm sure I'll use the axe for better things than pumpkins.~
@4094 = ~Oh, it’s you again! No worry, not in danger this time. Just split pumpkins.~
@4095 = ~Good to see you alive and you found peace.~
@4096 = ~Why pumpkins, of all things?~
@4097 = ~I’ll leave you to your pumpkins.~
@4098 = ~You kind. We thank again. You made new life for us.~
@4099 = ~You come to Duskwood Dell, we sing small thanks and share stew.~
@4100 = ~I may stop by.~
@4101 = ~Keep your songs for yourselves.~
@4102 = ~Good. You welcome. Eldath bless road that brought you.~
@4103 = ~As you wish. Still you saved us. We remember.~
@4104 = ~Pumpkin gives food. Pumpkin feels like head when smashing, but bursts not into blood.~
@4105 = ~Axe still heavy, but heart lighter. Pumpkins need split — we busy and happy.~
@4106 = ~Sounds peaceful indeed.~
@4107 = ~You could be lying to hide something.~
@4108 = ~Yes. Peace good. Thank you.~
@4109 = ~We not hide. You watch. If we fight, you see. If we not, you see also.~
@4110 = ~Farewell then. Keep axe sharp, friend — but for pumpkin now!~
@4111 = ~Thank you for saving us!~
@4112 = ~Excuse me... You're the one who helped our High Priest, aren't you? I was wondering if you might help me as well... just for a moment.~
@4113 = ~Depends. What do you need?~
@4114 = ~I have no time on helping boys that do not even shave themselves yet. Go play in the trees.~
@4115 = ~You see, it was recently that I run away from home. I... I just couldn't live the life I was expected to live! My parents passed when I was still young, and I was raised by my aunt—Pesca. She lives in the Government District of Athkatla. Her world is... marble, silk, and coin. She wanted me to become a refined, wealthy man. Privileged. Preening. Pampered.~
@4116 = ~But none of it ever felt like mine. Not the clothes, not the manners, not the future. One day, I heard something—felt something. A stillness. A call. Eldath’s voice in the wind, maybe.~
@4117 = ~So I came here, to Duskwood Dell, to learn, to breathe, to find a path of my own. But... I left without a word. Just vanished. That wasn’t right.~
@4118 = ~I can't return—she'd never let me go again. But maybe, if someone brought her this flower... told her I'm safe and where I am... maybe then, peace can grow between us again.~
@4119 = ~She's living in Athkatla. She often walks through the gardens of the Government District. Will you take this flower to her, and pass on my message?~
@4120 = ~Alright. I’ll do it.~
@4121 = ~That’s your problem, not mine.~
@4122 = ~Truly? Thank you. Here—take it. She rarely leaves the District; she always said the City of Coins was all she needed.~
@4123 = ~Let me know once you’ve given it to her. I’d really appreciate it.~
@4124 = ~R-right... I’m sorry to have bothered you.~
@4125 = ~I really hope my aunt will understand I needed to breath. That I needed something else than she does. I didn’t run from her—I ran toward something I needed.~
@4126 = ~I passed your message and gave the flower to your aunt. She suggested that maybe in a while you should give her some flowers on your own.~
@4127 = ~I gave her the flower. I’m not surprised you left. She seems... horrible.~
@4128 = ~Hmm.~
@4129 = ~She said that? Huh... I wasn’t expecting that.~
@4130 = ~Well, she's not THAT bad. I mean... she can be nice sometimes.~
@4131 = ~Thank you for doing this. It means more than I can say. Now that she knows I’m safe, I can truly begin focusing on what matters.~
@4132 = ~Whatever that is, exactly. Still figuring that out. But thanks. Really. You’re alright.~
@4133 = ~Peace be with you! You carry the scent of earth and danger—were you in some ruin or dark place? I’m not sure I’m made for such paths… but I hope the stillness I find here helps someone, too.~
@4134 = ~What is this rabble now? I have neither time nor patience for unsolicited interruptions. Be gone, unless you bear something of true importance.~
@4135 = ~Actually, I believe I do. I spoke to your nephew. He left because he wishes to discover life on his own terms. But he wanted you to know he’s well—and he asked me to give you this flower.~
@4136 = ~Right. I'll be leaving then.~
@4137 = ~He did what? He’s alive? I thought… I feared the worst. And yet he runs off, vanishing without so much as a word? The audacity!~
@4138 = ~Ungrateful whelp! I sheltered him, clothed him, educated him, gave him *everything*—and this is how he repays me?~
@4139 = ~Perhaps that’s exactly the problem.~
@4140 = ~Look, madam, I’m just delivering a message. He’s safe. You’ll see him again, I’m sure. That’s all you need to know.~
@4141 = ~How dare you imply such a thing?~
@4142 = ~He wants to live his own life. To make his own mistakes. He knows you meant well—but he needs to find his own way.~
@4143 = ~And what, pray tell, did he lack here? We have everything—comfort, beauty, security! Look at this district! There’s nothing beyond these walls that could serve him better than what I’ve already provided.~
@4144 = ~He’s fine. Just… give him time. Let him stumble. Let him grow.~
@4145 = ~I…~
@4146 = ~He’s doing well. Try to focus on that.~
@4147 = ~Very well. Tell him… tell him that next time, he ought to bring me the flowers himself. Hmph. That impudent, stupid, beloved boy!~
@4148 = ~Hmph! Then begone, meddler, and take your leave from my sight!~
@4149 = ~Hey! You've got worms?~
@4150 = ~No, I'm of very good health.~
@4151 = ~Erm, I don't think so. Sorry.~
@4152 = ~I'm not even going to answer that question. Goodbye.~
@4153 = ~How does a child like you end up in a place like this?~
@4154 = ~What—ew! It's not what I meant!~
@4155 = ~Oh... okay. A pity, though.~
@4156 = ~I’m an orphan. The priests here took me in when I had nowhere else to go. They say the goddess doesn’t turn away even the smallest leaf caught in the current.~
@4157 = ~Anyway… are you gonna help me find worms, or not?~
@4158 = ~I REALLY want to catch some good fish and show everyone what a good fisher-boy I can be! But I need a nice fat worm to do that! Let me know if you find one!~
@4159 = ~There must be some worm around here...~
@4160 = ~Eh, still no luck with all that worm-hunting job. Seriously, how hard it can be. Where are all the worms when a man needs one! I've looked everywhere.~
@4161 = ~Guess what! I've got a worm for you.~
@4162 = ~Patience. You'll find it.~
@4163 = ~You do?! That's amazing!~
@4164 = ~Just look how big it is! And how pink! And he moves in such a funny way!~
@4165 = ~Sorry, but I'll need to put you on the hook now. I really hope it's not gonna hurt you that much.~
@4166 = ~...~
@4167 = ~...erm...~
@4168 = ~Oh shoot. I cannot just kill him. He looks so nice. And I... I just wanna call him "Noodle" and teach him tricks!~
@4169 = ~You were supposed to be a fish food!~
@4170 = ~It looks like you just like him too much.~
@4171 = ~Ugh, I'm tired with this. (Take the worm and throw it into the water)~
@4172 = ~I kinda do.~
@4173 = ~Eh, I suppose I won't become a fisher-boy, then. But you know what? I can become a worm-trainer!~
@4174 = ~Thanks for bringing him to me. I think we're gonna be good friends.~
@4175 = ~What?! What have you done! You are sooo stupid and I'm gonna tell everyone you're horrible and that you're awful! And no one is going to like you! EVER!~
@4176 = ~Hey! You know what? I taught Noodle a new trick! Maybe I'm gonna show you next time.~
@4177 = ~Eldath watch over you, my friend. It is a blessing to meet another soul who walks in peace.~
@4178 = ~I think you deserve this. This is the emblem of Eldath that Merethan carried when he passed. I believe he would have wanted it to be used again.~
@4179 = ~I have spoken with Alatoasz. He agrees—you are worthy to bear Merethan’s emblem.~
@4180 = ~You seem calm and content. Have you lived here long, priestess?~
@4181 = ~How do you like this place, priestess? Duskwood Dell seems like a tranquil enclave in a troubled world.~
@4182 = ~This isn't my concern. Goodbye.~
@4183 = ~May peace flow with you. Farewell.~
@4184 = ~I met a sirine, full of anger. You live by peace and calm—can you tell me how to help her?~
@4185 = ~Oh yes, I have been here for many years, surrounded by gentle souls and the endless murmur of the waters.~
@4186 = ~I once spent my days carving the emblem of our Lady into wood and stone... but my hands no longer obey me as they once did.~
@4187 = ~Oh, how I wish I could carve one of the beautiful symbols of Eldath myself again, just as I once did! Still, I do not mourn what time has taken.~
@4188 = ~Now I teach the younger ones to carve instead. Their hands are my hands, and through them, the Lady’s symbols continue to bloom. I also taught Merethan how to carve his emblem. It is a pity he could not bring more peace into the world before the Goddess called him home.~
@4189 = ~Well then, tell me—have you come seeking something, or simply resting your spirit for a while?~
@4190 = ~No. I need to go, I'm done listening to your babbling.~
@4191 = ~No, I only wished you a peaceful day, my friend.~
@4192 = ~Yes... this place is peace made visible. After all this noise and haste, it is a gift to listen to silence.~
@4193 = ~The river never hurries, and yet it reaches the sea. There is wisdom in that, I think.~
@4194 = ~Your words are peaceful, yet they carry a hint of reflection. Do you miss your old duties?~
@4195 = ~Right. Whatever. I need to go.~
@4196 = ~Thank you for sharing that peace with me.~
@4197 = ~You would offer me Merethan's emblem? That is a great honor... but I cannot accept it lightly. Such a decision must come from the High Fallskeeper himself.~
@4198 = ~Shall I speak to the High Fallskeeper on your behalf?~
@4199 = ~I have already spoken with him. He wishes for you to carry it.~
@4200 = ~It was only an idea. I have other matters to attend to.~
@4201 = ~That would be a kindness beyond measure. Still, know that even if he refuses, I will not feel less blessed. The Lady teaches that peace lies in acceptance.~
@4202 = ~The High Fallskeeper grants me the honor of carrying Merethan’s emblem? Then peace truly circles back upon itself. Such kindness ripples farther than any river.~
@4203 = ~I have nothing but gratitude to offer, yet know that I shall carry your name in prayer to the Lady of Still Waters.~
@4204 = ~Thanks to you, I walk in peace once more—slowly, yes, but each step is a prayer.~
@4205 = ~Farewell, then. My hands may tremble, but my heart is steady. May yours be likewise, wherever your path flows.~
@4206 = ~My sister of the tides wanders lost in her fury, unable to hear the whispers of still water?~
@4207 = ~Bring her this. Blessed water mingled with chamomile, wild honey, blackberry, and lavender—each a whisper of calm from the grove. May it melt her wrath like morning sun on winter frost, leaving only quiet within.~
@4208 = ~Perhaps we could offer some of that brew to our angry dwarf here as well?~
@4209 = ~Ha! Very funny, half-elf! My rage bows to no potion—and that’s the way I like it! Now shut yer mouth before I find a new reason to get truly mad!~
@4210 = ~Let my siren sister drink this potion beneath the open sky. If her spirit is willing, Eldath’s calm will seep through the anger like sunlight thawing frozen waters.~
@4211 = ~Thank you, this will help her.~
@4212 = ~Hopefully this will work.~
@4213 = ~Alright. I'll bring your brew to your salty sister.~
@4214 = ~Carry calm as your shield, and kindness as your blade.~
@4215 = ~Argh!~ [SIRIN03]
@4216 = ~Well, it looks like someone's angry.~
@4217 = ~You’re the only one in this place who does not show harmony.~
@4218 = ~I think I'll leave you be.~
@4219 = ~Of course I’m angry! When all songs of the world turn to screams, how could I not be? The Realms shudder with war and madness, as if Toril itself has gone mad.~
@4220 = ~I came here after my kin clashed with pirates. I saw death... blood... sorrow. Far too much. And now it burns in me—with every breath.~
@4221 = ~Sometimes I just want to draw another arrow and end it all—to force the world into peace, if that’s what it takes.~
@4222 = ~But I sought peace, not vengeance. So when Eldath’s voice reached me—gentle as waves upon a sleeping shore—I thought I could let the fury sink. But it clings to me still, like seaweed around the heart.~
@4223 = ~I'm really sorry to hear that.~
@4224 = ~I didn’t know Eldath’s call reached voices like yours.~
@4225 = ~I don’t think I care about this. I think I’ll just go.~
@4226 = ~Surprised? So was I. But even storm-bound hearts crave calm. And hers was the only voice that didn’t ask for blood.~
@4227 = ~Interesting.~
@4228 = ~My heart mourns, truly it does... but the fury howls within me like a rising tide.~
@4229 = ~Then go. Leave. The sooner you're gone, the quieter it gets.~
@4230 = ~Argh!~
@4231 = ~I'll just leave you be.~
@4232 = ~I spoke with an old Eldathyn priestess. She believes you must accept that some anger will remain. She gave me this herbal brew to help you find calm.~
@4233 = ~Here — a mouthful of this herbal brew, and your troubles will be gone. Or so the old lady claims.~
@4234 = ~Herbal brew? You think a few sips will make me forget all the terrible things I’ve seen?~
@4235 = ~Well, it might be worth a try.~
@4236 = ~Do you have a better idea?~
@4237 = ~To be honest: No.~
@4238 = ~Do as you wish. I tried to help, but perhaps you're not ready to feel better.~
@4239 = ~Well... I suppose I can at least give it a chance.~
@4240 = ~It does feel... comfortable.~
@4241 = ~See? That wasn’t so hard.~
@4242 = ~That went better than I expected.~
@4243 = ~Just enjoy this moment. I’ll leave you now.~
@4244 = ~A breath of calm at last... the only weight I still carry is this quiver of arrows, forever reminding me of the life I once led.~
@4245 = ~I’ve held these arrows close for longer than I can remember, but now I feel them pulling me back instead of setting me free — at least within these waters.~
@4246 = ~You, on the other hand, look like someone who can still make use of them. Take them. They have served me well, but I think they might serve you better. You have my thanks... and perhaps a measure of my peace.~
@4247 = ~I’d rather not talk right now... I just want to watch the water.~
@4248 = ~I don’t know why I ever thought this place would make things better...~
@4249 = ~*sigh*~
